Summary 05 of the book of Christian Theology

The third source of theology is the intelligence of humanity. Christian theology admits the importance of intelligence, however, what's the relation between theology and intelligence?

First is that theology is a reasonable study, the belief of Christianity based on reasonable fundamentals and intelligence can be used as a tool to explore the belief. But Christianity is not restricted to intelligence only, our faith is above intelligence, but uses intelligence as a tool to order the divine revelation and to get the meaning hidden in the revelation.

Second is that theology follows the insight of intelligence fully. Contrary to the above one's opinion, someone admired intelligence and thought all the faith of Christianity comes from intelligence, humans can get the whole religious things by intelligence only.

Afterward, the above opinion became the opinion that "Christianity is the concept which can be proved". Thus those signs which cannot be proved were denied and discarded. This means intelligence is superior to revelation.

Third is that theology is dominated by intelligence. According to this opinion, intelligence has the authority to judge the religion. This approach is related with deism, which believes in the existence of God as a creator, but God does not intervene in the creature. Contrary with deism, theism believes in the existence of one God as the creator and believes Him intervening in the creature.

The enlightening rationalism believes we can get all the knowledge about ourselves and God as we need, perfectly. This opinion thinks intelligence could remove the mist and darkness of christian belief to show the glorious light of the rationality of humanity.

Let's identify the difference between "intelligence" and "rationalism" first. The word "intelligence" means the thinking ability of humans based on evidence and demonstration, and when we think of intelligence as the only source of divine knowledge, "intelligence" becomes "rationalism".

The flaw of rationalism is that there isn't any universal rationality. Many people claimed their ideas were rational and should be respected, but the "universal rationality" to decide those rationality does not exist.

Besides intelligence, the experience can be another source of theology. Experience means "the things in our life journey", "the knowledge accumulated through our personal life". Afterward, the word "experience" has one more meaning: personal emotion of one's inside life.

Religious Experience is important in Methodism, as the one side of "Wesleyan quadrilateral", and the other three sides are "scripture", "tradition" and "intelligence". Wesley stressed that believers should receive the message in the scripture by living faith and experience the presence of God.

According to William James, there are 4 characters of religious experience: ineffability, noetic quality, transiency, and passivity.

Ineffability means "religious experience cannot be expressed or described in words"; noetic quality means "religious experience gives us the knowledge and insight of the supertemporal truth"; transiency means "religious experience lasting only for a short time from 30 minutes to 2 hours"; passivity means "religious experience is a passive experience".

There are four approaches to get the relation between theology and religious experience: experience as the baseline data of christian theology; theology connected with experience; theology is the framework to explain experience; god is just the objectified experience.

Personally, I dislike those believers who claim their "religious experience", maybe it's because I'm jealous about their "religious experience", such as the ability of "tongue" to make some voice no one understands even himself. Those experiences showed their special, close relationship with God, it makes me feel I'm wrong without those special, I'd like to call it "strange" experience.

Moreover, I'm afraid of those men or women who claim their "religious experience", it seems like their words come from God that I must obey them, if not, I will be attacked by them in the name of God. However, maybe it's just because I don't have such experience, and maybe it's because I think those experiences are strange, and stopped them from beginning. I'm afraid of any strange experience. I don't want to be a man who claims his personal experience as the proof of his holiness. The proof only in the mouth of Jesus Christ, most self-proof is just self-deceive.

